
Since you’re working with OpenShift clusters already, I’ll explain OpenShift in a low-level (internal architecture) way — similar to how kernel/system engineers analyze platforms. This focuses on internal daemons, processes, control loops, and data flow, not just concepts.


---

1. OpenShift Low-Level Architecture

OpenShift is essentially:

Linux OS (RHCOS)
        ↓
Container Runtime (CRI-O)
        ↓
Kubernetes Control Plane
        ↓
OpenShift Platform Operators
        ↓
Applications (Pods)

Main building blocks:

1. Linux kernel


2. Container runtime


3. Kubernetes control plane


4. Operators


5. Platform services




---

2. Operating System Layer

OpenShift nodes run
Red Hat Enterprise Linux CoreOS (RHCOS)

RHCOS characteristics

Immutable OS

OSTree based

Managed by MachineConfigOperator

Automatic OS updates


Key components running on node:

systemd
kubelet
cri-o
NetworkManager
ovs-vswitchd
ovn-controller

Example:

ps -ef | grep kubelet
ps -ef | grep crio


---

3. Container Runtime Layer

OpenShift uses
CRI-O

instead of Docker.

Runtime architecture

Kubelet
   │
   │ CRI (gRPC)
   ▼
CRI-O
   │
   │ OCI runtime
   ▼
runc
   │
   ▼
Linux Kernel (namespaces + cgroups)

Container creation flow

1️⃣ Kubelet receives pod spec

2️⃣ kubelet → CRI request

RunPodSandbox()
CreateContainer()
StartContainer()

3️⃣ CRI-O pulls image

/var/lib/containers/storage

4️⃣ runc creates container

Kernel features used:

cgroups
namespaces
seccomp
SELinux


---

4. Kubernetes Control Plane (Internal)

OpenShift control plane runs:

kube-apiserver
kube-controller-manager
kube-scheduler
etcd

All are static pods on master nodes.

Example:

/etc/kubernetes/manifests/

Files:

kube-apiserver-pod.yaml
kube-controller-manager.yaml
kube-scheduler.yaml

Kubelet monitors these files.

If container crashes → kubelet restarts automatically.


