1. Complete OpenShift Control Plane Architecture

OpenShift control plane runs on master nodes.

Typical deployment:

3 control plane nodes

Core components come from
Kubernetes and are extended by
Red Hat OpenShift Container Platform.


---

Control Plane Components

1. kube-apiserver

Central entry point of the cluster.

Responsibilities:

REST API

authentication

authorization

admission control

communication with etcd


Example request:

kubectl get pods

Flow:

kubectl
   ↓
API Server
   ↓
etcd

API server runs stateless and horizontally scalable.


---

2. etcd

Distributed key-value database.

Stores:

cluster state
pod specs
node status
configmaps
secrets

Example key:

/registry/pods/default/nginx

OpenShift typically runs 3 etcd members for quorum.


---

3. kube-scheduler

Scheduler assigns pods to nodes.

Algorithm considers:

CPU
memory
affinity
taints/tolerations
topology

Process:

watch pod
↓
filter nodes
↓
score nodes
↓
bind pod to node


---

4. kube-controller-manager

Runs multiple control loops.

Controllers include:

node controller
replica controller
deployment controller
service controller
endpoints controller

Controller logic:

desired state
↓
compare with actual state
↓
take action


---

5. OpenShift Platform Controllers

OpenShift adds platform operators such as:

cluster-version-operator
machine-config-operator
authentication-operator
ingress-operator

These manage platform lifecycle.


