3. How OpenShift Operators Upgrade the Cluster

The upgrade is controlled by the Cluster Version Operator.

Operator architecture is part of
Operator Framework.


---

Upgrade Trigger

Admin runs:

oc adm upgrade

or via web console.


---

Upgrade Workflow

ClusterVersionOperator
        │
        ▼
download release image
        │
        ▼
extract manifests
        │
        ▼
upgrade platform operators
        │
        ▼
upgrade control plane
        │
        ▼
upgrade worker nodes

Release image contains:

all operators
kubernetes manifests
container images


---

Control Plane Upgrade

Steps:

1 API server updated
2 controller manager updated
3 scheduler updated
4 etcd updated

Each step ensures cluster health before next stage.


---

Worker Node Upgrade

Handled by Machine Config Operator.

Process:

cordon node
↓
drain workloads
↓
update OS (RHCOS)
↓
reboot node
↓
uncordon node

OS update uses OSTree atomic update.


---

4. How etcd Stores Kubernetes Objects Internally

etcd is a distributed key-value store.

Data model:

key → value

Keys represent Kubernetes objects.


---

Example Object

Pod:

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: nginx

Stored as:

/registry/pods/default/nginx

Value contains serialized object.

Serialization format:

protobuf


---

etcd Internal Structure

Disk storage:

/var/lib/etcd/member/

Important files:

snap/db
wal/

Components:

WAL (write ahead log)
snapshot
b-tree index


---

Write Operation

When API server writes data:

client request
 ↓
API server validation
 ↓
etcd write request
 ↓
WAL append
 ↓
commit to raft quorum

Cluster consensus uses:

Raft algorithm

Majority required:

2 of 3 nodes


